202F.description: Under supervision, students perform a complete history and physical exam on hospitalized or clinic patients five times during the semester. They present the patients in written and verbal format to the instructor and class. These presentations are critiqued and the tools to effectively present cases are taught. The course runs for the first half of the student's last semester in the program. Each student is required to turn in three patient write-ups.
202F.title: Clinical Skills 6

98.description: Organized group study on topics selected by Health and Medical Sciences faculty for freshman/sophomore students.
98.title: Directed Group Study

262.description: The Qualitative Analysis TWG provides JMP students a supportive small group student-centered environment in which to discuss their qualitative research with other students engaged in qualitative research towards the goal of the successful completion of the required JMP MS.
262.title: Qualitative Analysis Thesis Working Group

298.description: Group study for graduate students. Intensive examination of health-related topics.
298.title: Directed Group Study

200D.description: The six semester sequence (200A-200F) introducing principles of the medical basic science, health policy, public health, and clinical aspects of medicine taught in a contextual-integrated case-based format. The sequence includes curriculum in biochemistry, histology, microbiology, immunology, neuroanatomy, pathology, physiology, pharmacology, and clinical sciences.
200D.title: Contextual Integrated Case-Based Curriculum

265.description: The Epidemiology/Reproductive Health/ Evaluation TWG provides JMP students a supportive small group student-centered environment in which to discuss their research with other students engaged in Epidemiology/Reproductive Health/ Evaluation projects towards the goal of the successful completion of the required JMP MS.
265.title: Epidemiology/Reproductive Health/Evaluation Research Thesis Working Group

197.description: Field experience relevant to health and medical sciences. Regular individual and/or group meetings with faculty sponsor are required. A final written report or ongoing field notebook is required. One unit of credit represents three hours of work per week on the part of the student.
197.title: Field Study in Health and Medical Sciences

261.description: A seminar to help Joint Medical Program students acquire skills necessary to define a research question, find appropriate mentorship, and design a research project. Summer course introduces research design, methods, and expectations for M.S. research in Health and Medical Sciences. Fall and spring semesters address topics in research; student progress toward M.S. thesis is reviewed and critiqued. Development of research plan, protocol design and implementation, and research findings will be reviewed. Each student takes this course three times in the first year.
261.title: Research Seminar

200F.description: The six semester sequence (200A-200F) introducing principles of the medical basic science, health policy, public health, and clinical aspects of medicine taught in a contextual-integrated case-based format. The sequence includes curriculum in biochemistry, histology, microbiology, immunology, neuroanatomy, pathology, physiology, pharmacology, and clinical sciences.
200F.title: Contextual Integrated Case-Based Curriculum

202B.description: Students learn the cardiovascular, pulmonary, eye, and gastrointestinal exam and practice a complete medical history and physical exam with their preceptor. The dynamics of the physician-patient relationship are discussed on an ongoing basis with both the preceptor and the faculty instructor. Each student is required to turn in at least five patient write-ups per term.
202B.title: Clinical Skills 2

296.description: Designed to permit qualified graduate students to pursue special study under the direction of a faculty member.
296.title: Special Study

200B.description: The six semester sequence (200A-200F) introducing principles of the medical basic science, health policy, public health, and clinical aspects of medicine taught in a contextual-integrated case-based format. The sequence includes curriculum in biochemistry, histology, microbiology, immunology, neuroanatomy, pathology, physiology, pharmacology, and clinical sciences.
200B.title: Contextual Integrated Case-Based Curriculum

264.description: The Mixed Methods/Community-based Research TWG provides JMP students a supportive small group student-centered environment in which to discuss their research with other students engaged or interested in mixed methods/community-based research projects towards the goal of the successful completion of the required JMP MS.
264.title: Mixed Methods/Community-Based Research Thesis Working Group

299.description: Independent study, research, and writing in an area related to program of study, sponsored by an approved faculty member and approved by program adviser.
299.title: Independent Study and Research in Health and Medical Sciences

202D.description: Students learn the male genito-urinary exam and practice the complete medical history and physical exam with their preceptor. The dynamics of the physician-patient relationship are discussed on an ongoing basis. Each student is required to turn in at least five patient write-ups per term.
202D.title: Clinical Skills 4

266.description: The Clinical Medicine/Bench Research/Clinical Epi/Behavioral TWG provides JMP students a supportive small group student-centered environment in which to discuss their Clinical Medicine/Bench Research/Clinical Epi/Behavioral projects towards the goal of the successful completion of the required JMP MS.
266.title: Clinical Medicine/Bench Research/Clinical Epi/Behavioral Thesis Working Group

267.description: The Bioethics, Medical Humanities TWG provides JMP students a supportive small group student-centered environment in which to discuss their research with other students engaged in Bioethics, Medical Humanities projects towards the goal of the successful completion of the required JMP MS.
267.title: Bioethics, Medical Humanities, or Archival Thesis Working Group

211.description: All aspects of basic neurobiology needed for medical education will be covered, including central nervous processing, sensory input, motor input and consideration of complex functions as learning and consciousness. Intensive student work in preparation of material presented and the use of clinical correlates and problems will emphasize the role of neurobiology in clinical medicine.
211.title: Narrative and Medicine
